flds.name: Hide others on the back side

note_models.name: Cloze (Hide all)

tmpls.afmt:
<script>
/* --- DO NOT DELETE OR EDIT THIS SCRIPT --- */
setTimeout(function() {
    var clozeBoxes = document.querySelector(".cloze cloze2_w");
    var elements = document.querySelectorAll("cloze2." + clozeBoxes.className);
    for(var i = 0 ; i < elements.length ; i++) {
        elements[i].classList.add("cloze");
        elements[i].style.display="inline";
    }
}, 0);
/* --- DO NOT DELETE OR EDIT THIS SCRIPT --- */
</script>



{{cloze:Text}}
{{#Extra}}
<hr>
{{Extra}}
{{/Extra}}

{{#Hide others on the back side}}
<style>
cloze2 {
    display: none;
}

cloze2_w {
    display: inline-block;
    width: 5em;
    height: 1em;
    background-color: #ffeba2;
}

.cloze cloze2 {
    display: inline;
}

.cloze cloze2_w {
    display: none;
}

cloze2.reveal-cloze2 {
    display: inline;
}

cloze2_w.reveal-cloze2 {
    display: none;
}

.cloze2-toggle {
    -webkit-appearance: none;
    display: block;
    font-size: 1.3em;
    height: 2em;
    background-color: #ffffff;
    width: 100%;
    margin-top: 20px;
}

.cloze2-toggle:active {
    background-color: #ffffaa;
}
</style>

<script>
function toggle() {
var elements = document.querySelectorAll('cloze2, cloze2_w');
    for(var i = 0 ; i < elements.length ; i++) {
        elements[i].classList.toggle('reveal-cloze2');
    }
}
</script>

<button class='cloze2-toggle' onclick='toggle()'>Toogle mask</button>
{{/Hide others on the back side}}

fields: Actin filaments can form {{c1::stress fibers}} which allow for cellular "crawling."
Actin is found in {{c1::muscle fibers}} and {{c2::most cells as part of a submembrane network}}

Polymerization and depolymerization, and organizing of filaments are regulated by:
{{c1::actin-binding proteins}}
{{c1::severing proteins}}
{{c1::bundling proteins}}
{{c1::changes in Ca2+}}
{{c1::changes in cAMP}}
Intermediate filaments are typically {{c1::10-12 nm}} in diameter
{{c1::Intermediate filaments}} are more stable and more variable than other cytoskeletal elements.
Intermediate filaments form {{c1::coiled-coil dimers}} which organize themselves into {{c2::tetramers}}
{{c1::Keratins}} are {{c1::intermediate filaments}} found in epithelial cells and are abundant in the surface layer of the epidermis.
Keratins are found in {{c1::hair, nails, horns, and hoofs.}}
Vimentin and vimentin-like proteins are found in tissues derived from {{c1::mesenchyme}}
{{c1::Neurofilaments}} are intermediate filaments found only in neurons.
Lamins are found in {{c1::cell nuclei}} and function as {{c1::a structural framework of the nucleus.}}
{{c1::Keratins}} are present where a lot of abrasion occurs.
